name: cable production, connector for computer, without plugs | cable, connector for computer, without plugs | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/5169/documentation

This dataset represents the production of 1 m of a typical power cord/connector for a desktop computer. It is based on a Swiss system cable, with 0.75 mm2 cross-section, Type H05VV-F, LS-60, and 3 conductor pins, of recent date and designed to handle 10A and ca. 250V with a weight of 0.065 kg (without plugs). Main data are based on weighting and calculations of a Swiss type computer cable at EMPA la-boratories, supported by EPD information.;[This dataset was already contained in the ecoinvent database version 2. It was not individually updated during the transfer to ecoinvent version 3. Life Cycle Impact Assessment results may still have changed, as they are affected by changes in the supply chain, i.e. in other datasets. This dataset was generated following the ecoinvent quality guidelines for version 2. It may have been subject to central changes described in the ecoinvent version 3 change report (http://www.ecoinvent.org/database/ecoinvent-version-3/reports-of-changes/), and the results of the central updates were reviewed extensively. The changes added e.g. consistent water flows and other information throughout the database. The documentation of this dataset can be found in the ecoinvent reports of version 2, which are still available via the ecoinvent website. The change report linked above covers all central changes that were made during the conversion process.]

From reception of metal and plastic materials at the factory gate.

This dataset includes materials copper, TPE (elastomere) and PVC with their respective manufacturing processes, infrastructure, electricity for the assembly, fuel oil, propane and water input, the disposal of plastic and rubber parts, the VOC and methanol emissions created during the processing, plus the road and rail transportation for input materials from the regional storage to the production site. The accumulated hazardous waste is also reported.
category: C:Manufacturing/26:Manufacture of computer, electronic and optical products/261:Manufacture of electronic components and boards/2610:Manufacture of electronic components and boards

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: The data describes a typical computer cable in 2006. The kind of cable is produced by international manufacturers and available all over the world. Therefore a global dataset is justifiable.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: The manufacturing process is inventoried through wire drawing and extrusion of insulation and jacket (TPE, PVC) around wire. Cable manufacturing is a process that typically is composed of: Insulation of copper conductors or optical fibres with selected polymer(s);  If specified, shielding of insulated copper conductors (based on cable design); If specified, twisting of insulated conductors into pairs or triplets or quads (based on cable design); If specified, shielding of insulated pairs, triplets, or quads (based on cable design); Cabling of insulated conductors and/or pairs, triplets, quads into groups (based on cable de-sign); If specified, shielding of group(s) of conductors/pairs/triplets (based on cable design); Cabling of together unshielded and shielded groups of conductors into the cable bundle; If specified, overall shielding of cable bundle (based on cable design); If specified, application of separation barriers around cable bundle and/or overall shield; Jacketing over cable bundle or shielded cable bundle with selected polymer; Perform outgoing QA testing (tests based on cable design).
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: Weighing and measuring of materials. Literature for electricity consumption (assembly), emissions and waste.

exchanges.description:
EcoSpold01Location=GLO
A computer power cable is a cable that temporarily connects an electrical appliance to an electrical power source. The term is generally used for cables using a power plug to connect to a single-phase alternating current power source at "mains voltage" (100 to 240 volts, depending on the location). The term ‘cord set’ is also used to distinguish those cords that include connectors molded to the cord at each end. Power cords from those countries that use 110 V mains supply (mainly the United States, Canada, parts of South America and Japan) tend to be bulkier than the mains cables used in the rest of the world, because of the higher currents required to deliver the same power (watts) at 110 V compared to 230 V. 
Power cables may be either fixed or detachable from the appliance. In the case of detachable leads (plugs), the appliance end of the power cord has a socket (female connector) rather than a plug (male connector) to link it to the appliance, to avoid the dangers from having a live protruding pin. Cords may also have twist-locking features, or other attachments to prevent accidental disconnection at one or both ends
